data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never raised — dead code |

`Thread.Abort` was removed because it corrupts application state by injecting exceptions at arbitrary points (mid-lock, mid-write, mid-finally). .NET 8 uses **cooperative cancellation** instead.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must observe the CancellationToken to be stoppable.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single exceptions to match original behavior.
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }

        return task.Result;
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async-native overload — prefer this in new code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Migration Pitfalls

**1. Work must cooperate — cancellation is no longer forced**

```csharp
// ❌ Old call site — work ignores cancellation, will run forever on timeout
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct => SlowComputation(), timeout);

// ✅ Work must check the token
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // exit point
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, timeout);
```

**2. Wrapping uncooperative code (e.g., third-party libs)**

If you truly cannot modify the work, you can abandon (not abort) the thread — but it **leaks**:

```csharp
// Fire-and-forget fallback — the thread keeps running but you stop waiting.
// Use only as a last resort for unmodifiable code.
public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    T result = default!;
    Exception? error = null;

    var thread = new Thread(() =>
    {
        try { result = work(); }
        catch (Exception ex) { error = ex; }
    }) { IsBackground = true };  // won't block process exit

    thread.Start();

    if (!thread.Join(timeout))
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");

    if (error != null)
        throw new AggregateException(error);

    return result;
}
```

**3. Signature change breaks callers**

The new `Func<CancellationToken, T>` signature is source-breaking. For a gradual migration, provide both overloads:

```csharp
// Compat shim — delegates to the new implementation
[Obsolete("Pass a CancellationToken-aware delegate for proper timeout support.")]
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    => ExecuteWithTimeout(ct => work(), timeout);
```

**4. `Task.Run` uses the ThreadPool, not a dedicated thread**

The original created a new `Thread` each call. `Task.Run` uses the pool, which is better for throughput but means long-blocking work can starve other tasks. For CPU-heavy isolation, use `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`.
